Serve real container ids from a daemon cache

The previous iteration (already merged) made plain "rumpel list" show
the CONTAINER ID column by deriving the backend container name from
the repo path and pod name, replacing the docker hash id and dropping
the 12-char truncation. That conflated the availability fix with a
change of the column's meaning. Restore the original output (docker
container id, kubernetes pod name, 12-char truncation) and keep it
available without --sync via an in-memory cache in the daemon.

The cache is filled at launch (docker create prints the id on stdout,
so no extra query) and by the same per-host queries --sync runs;
entries are dropped at every site where the daemon deletes a
container, so a recreate never shows a stale id. Docker assigns ids
at creation and nothing persists them, so a restarted daemon
re-fetches them on the first list: hosts not yet reconciled this
daemon lifetime are queried once and then marked warmed, so pods
whose containers are gone do not trigger a backend query on every
list. SSH hosts are only queried while connected, as with --sync.
This avoids a DB schema change, for which there is no migration
story yet.
